## Overview 
The following process will allow you to integrate multiple Splunk Azure Add-ons using one application registration, instead of registering a unique application per Splunk add-on.  **This drastically reduces implementation and configuration time for Splunk engineers and Azure administrators.**   

After completing this process, **you will only need to note a single tenant ID, client ID and client secret for any Splunk add-ons for Microsoft Azure.** Your Azure administrator should be able to provide this to you when the integration is completed. 

For a birds-eye view of existing Splunk Azure integrations, please see [Azure/O365 Splunk Add-on Required Permissions](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1YJAqNmcXZU-7O9CxVKupOkR6q2S8TXriMeLAUMYmMs4/edit#gid=0)

*Ensure you review the details and documentation on [Splunkbase](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/) for each add-on linked in the spreadsheet for additional context.*

### Steps 

The source reference from [Ciraltos](https://www.ciraltos.com/) has excellent instructions but outdated screenshots, most Azure administrators should be able to interpret this guide: [Ciraltos Use Splunk to Collect Logs from Office 365 and Azure AD](https://www.ciraltos.com/use-splunk-to-collect-logs-from-office-365-and-azure-ad/)  

1. Follow the [Ciraltos guide](https://www.ciraltos.com/use-splunk-to-collect-logs-from-office-365-and-azure-ad/)   all the way down until **Log API Read Access.** This completes the integration for [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Office 365](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/4055/). 

2. Then you are free to reference the guide for [Azure/O365 Splunk Add-on Required Permissions](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1YJAqNmcXZU-7O9CxVKupOkR6q2S8TXriMeLAUMYmMs4/edit#gid=0) and add any additional rights for other Azure Add-ons.

3. When you have completed adding rights for any additional Azure add-ons, you can continue through the [Ciraltos guide](https://www.ciraltos.com/use-splunk-to-collect-logs-from-office-365-and-azure-ad/) to complete the Azure portion of the integration. Ensure you receive the **tenant ID, client ID and client secret** to complete the Splunk portion. 

4. After (or before), you can install the related Splunk add-ons for Azure to your deployment's heavy forwarder or IDM of your choosing, the search heads and indexers if necessary.  

5. Then enter the following in the related Splunk Add-ons under configuration:    
	- Tenant ID
	- Client ID
	- Client secret

## Splunk Add-ons for Azure Overview 
There are a variety of Splunk integrations for Azure technologies available on [Splunkbase](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/) the following is a detailed reference for the capabilities and requirements to integrate various Azure log streams into Splunk: [Azure/O365 Splunk Add-on Required Permissions](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1YJAqNmcXZU-7O9CxVKupOkR6q2S8TXriMeLAUMYmMs4/edit#gid=0)

  ### The (main) Add-ons <a id="main-azure-addons"></a>
Splunk security operations center engineers and analysts should prioritize the following 3 add-ons in the spreadsheet for security monitoring and compliance purposes:

-   [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Azure](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3110/) -  Active Directory Sign-ins, users, groups, audit risk detection, Security Center, etc., *(spreadsheet line 2)* 

-   [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Security](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/6207/) - Microsoft 365 Defender Incidents, endpoint alerts, *(spreadsheet line 7)* 
	*  Provides the following actions in Splunk Incident Review 
		* Defender Advanced Threat Hunting
		* Defender Update Incident 

-   [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Office 365](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/4055/) -  Message Trace, cloud application security, administrator management activity, audit logs, *(spreadsheet line 3)*
 
#### Honorable Mention 
- [Microsoft Graph Security API Add-on for Splunk](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/4564/) - May provide additional security context, *(spreadsheet line 8)* 
	- Occasionally required from teams familiar with this data 

### The (other) Add-ons <a id="other-azure-addons"></a>

 - [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Cloud Services](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3110/) - Azure Resources such as virtual machine data, virtual host IPs and subnets,  **provides capability to read custom logs from storage tables (such as Microsoft Intune)**, Event Hub, etc., *(spreadsheet line 1)* 

- [Microsoft O365 Email Add-on for Splunk](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/5365/) - Emails, email groups, *(spreadsheet line 5)* 

- [Microsoft Teams Add-on for Splunk](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/4994/) - User reports, call records, *(spreadsheet line 6)*  

- [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Office 365 Reporting Web Service (depreciated)](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3720/) - The functionality in this add-on has moved to the Splunk Add-on for Microsoft office 365, *(spreadsheet line 4)* 

## Existing Deployments
You can use an existing Splunk/Azure application registration and continue adding permissions to it via the [Azure/O365 Splunk Add-on Required Permissions](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1YJAqNmcXZU-7O9CxVKupOkR6q2S8TXriMeLAUMYmMs4/edit#gid=0) document, or you can follow the guidance on [Splunkbase](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/) for the individual Azure integrations. 

## WIP - Microsoft Intune <a id="intune"></a> <!-- ✏️ Date: 230107 -->

Please post comments, feedback and improvments to [Master Azure SOC Account - Discussions](https://github.com/tdmathis/tdmathis.github.io/discussions/1)

You can log a variety of logs to Microsoft storage containers, including Intune. **I've only done this once and I wrote this from memory, but I hope it points you in the right direction.** 

You will have to write custom extractions for this data source if you don't already have them, see [Disclaimer](#disclaimer). 

### Steps <a id="intune-steps"></a>

I recommend using the existing app registration outlined in this guide, but you are welcome to create a new app registration for this integration via Step 1 below. 

1. (Optional) - Add a unique Azure application account registration for Intune. 
 
	-- Open the Azure portal and go to **Azure AD > App Registrations > click New Registration.**  Give the App a name and add a Redirect URI.  The URI is not used, it can point to https://localhost.

3.  [Create Storage Account](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/storage/common/storage-account-create?tabs=azure-portal)  

	-- The storage account name **MUST** be lowercase
    
4.  Send your Intune logs to the storage account - [Send log data to storage, event hubs, or log analytics in Intune](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/mem/intune/fundamentals/review-logs-using-azure-monitor#send-logs-to-azure-monitor)

	-- The prerequisites on this step require the *List Keys* permission, I did not notice this requirement on my first pass and no additional configuration was necessary at the time

5. Request the storage account name (the lowercase value), the [storage account secret value](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/AddOns/released/MSCloudServices/Configurestorageaccount), and the storage account table name from the Azure administrator.  

	*You need the storage account table name for Step 7, I recall this populating automatically after selecting the Azure Storage Account under inputs, but just in-case, you can navigate to Azure AD > Storage Accounts > Select Account > Storage Tables  to view the list.*

6.  Install the [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Cloud Services](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3110/) and navigate to Configure > Add Azure App Account to enter the following:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

6.  Add the Storage Account to the [Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Cloud Services](https://splunkbase.splunk.com/app/3110/)
	
	-- Account Name should be the lowercase value
	
	-- Account Secret should be provided by the Azure Administrator: [Azure AD > Storage Accounts > Select Account > Security + Networking > Access Keys](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/AddOns/released/MSCloudServices/Configurestorageaccount)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

7. Create the input for Intune

	-- Azure AD > Storage Accounts > Select Account > Storage Tables to view the table name
	
	-- You can update the index and sourcetype below 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Disclaimer 
Intune is a PITA integration, open to feedback and collaboration.  I've only done this once and I pulled together a few resources to reinvent this ingestion, I hope this will at least point you in the right direction.  

It went smoothly at the time, and though this seems like the most straight forward way, the Microsoft docs provide alternate methods I haven't tested in production.  

One thing that stands out to me is step 3.c in [Microsoft's Intune logging documentation](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/mem/intune/fundamentals/review-logs-using-azure-monitor#send-logs-to-azure-monitor):
- **Stream to an event hub**: Streams the logs to an Azure event hub. **If you want analytics on your log data using SIEM tools, such as Splunk and QRadar, choose this option.**
	
	- For this choose your own adventure guide, I went with step 3.b 

- I haven't personally seen Intune logs from a event hub, and I am not clear if it differs from Intune storage account logs. 

- Azure Event Hub data comes in under one sourcetype: **mscs:azure:eventhub**
 
- If you are certain that Intune is the only data that will be coming in from this source then its fine, but in cases where multiple data streams are logged to the same event hub, it may be difficult to differentiate or CIM data in this sourcetype. 
	
	See the second screenshot on the second step that provides a sample of Active Directory logs via Event Hub.  Note that  the only clear sourcetype differentiator is the tail end of the resourceId: [How to: Integrate Azure Active Directory logs with Splunk using Azure Monitor](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/reports-monitoring/howto-integrate-activity-logs-with-splunk)

- If you have the opportunity to test and compare these ingestion methods, here is a link to Splunk docs on [Configure Azure Event Hub inputs for the Splunk Add-on for Microsoft Cloud Services](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/AddOns/released/MSCloudServices/Configureeventhubs)
